---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout title="Addressing — idr.to" description="v1 idrto URI grammar, DEF encoding, HTTPS mirror, and synthetic *.idr hostnames.">
  <Header slot="header" />
  <Footer slot="footer" />

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">v1 grammar</p>
      <h1>Addressing profiles</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        idr.to v1 uses a single logical model: <strong>host~entity-id</strong> is the
        <strong>Host-Identity</strong>; <strong>service-or-port</strong> selects the local workload. Four surface
        forms exist for different clients. Each machine also has a <strong>Device-ID</strong> (120-bit routing
        address); DEF encoding of the Host-Identity yields a globally routable <strong>FQHN</strong>.
      </p>

      <h2>Host-Identity, Device-ID &amp; FQHN</h2>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Description</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>entity-id</strong></td>
              <td>Globally unique owner namespace (email, domain, UUID)</td>
              <td><code>acme.com</code>, <code>user@example.com</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>host</strong></td>
              <td>Unique within an entity-id; dot-separated labels</td>
              <td><code>laptop</code>, <code>gpu-a.us-east</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Host-Identity</strong></td>
              <td><code>host~entity-id</code> — globally unique and addressable</td>
              <td><code>gpu-a.us-east~acme.com</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Device-ID</strong></td>
              <td>120-bit ID from Ed25519 public key; routing address (like IP in IP routing)</td>
              <td>First 120 bits of SHA-256(pubkey)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Synthetic FQHN</strong></td>
              <td>Tool-native hostname encoding Host-Identity (decoded locally)</td>
              <td><code>gpu-a.us-east.user-40acme-2Ecom.idr</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>DEF FQHN</strong></td>
              <td>Host-Identity DEF-encoded under <code>*.idr.to</code> — globally routable DNS</td>
              <td><code>dgpu-a-2eus-2deast-7eacme-2ecom.idr.to</code></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        Multiple machines (Device-IDs) may register the <strong>same</strong> host name — resolve round-robins
        among them (see advanced note below). The usual pattern is <strong>one host name per physical device</strong>
        under the same entity-id.
      </p>

      <h2 id="multiple-devices">One user, up to five devices</h2>
      <p>
        A Personal or Enterprise subscription covers <strong>one user</strong> and up to <strong>five registered
        machines</strong> (five Device-IDs). All devices share the same <strong>entity-id</strong> (your account).
        Give each machine its own <strong>host</strong> label so every device has a distinct, globally addressable
        Host-Identity:
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Machine</th>
              <th>Host</th>
              <th>Host-Identity</th>
              <th>Example idrto URI</th>
              <th>Synthetic FQHN</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Work laptop</td>
              <td><code>laptop</code></td>
              <td><code>laptop~user@example.com</code></td>
              <td><code>idrto:laptop~user-40example.com/ssh</code></td>
              <td><code>laptop.user-40example-2Ecom.idr</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>M4 Mac mini (Ollama)</td>
              <td><code>m4mini</code></td>
              <td><code>m4mini~user@example.com</code></td>
              <td><code>idrto:m4mini~user-40example.com/ollama</code></td>
              <td><code>m4mini.user-40example-2Ecom.idr</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Android phone</td>
              <td><code>mobile1</code></td>
              <td><code>mobile1~user@example.com</code></td>
              <td><code>idrto:mobile1~user-40example.com/ssh</code></td>
              <td><code>mobile1.user-40example-2Ecom.idr</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>iPhone</td>
              <td><code>mobile-apple</code></td>
              <td><code>mobile-apple~user@example.com</code></td>
              <td><code>idrto:mobile-apple~user-40example.com/ssh</code></td>
              <td><code>mobile-apple.user-40example-2Ecom.idr</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Home desktop</td>
              <td><code>desktop</code></td>
              <td><code>desktop~user@example.com</code></td>
              <td><code>idrto:desktop~user-40example.com/443</code></td>
              <td><code>desktop.user-40example-2Ecom.idr</code></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        Each row is a separate physical device with its own Device-ID and Ed25519 keypair. You connect to a
        <em>specific</em> machine by naming its host — e.g. SSH to the Mac mini:
        <code>ssh user@m4mini.user-40example-2Ecom.idr</code>, not to a generic “my account” alias.
      </p>
      <pre><code># On the Mac mini (device 2 of 5) — same entity, different host
idr auth login                    # entity user@example.com
idr device register --name m4mini
idr host register m4mini          # Host-Identity m4mini~user@example.com
idr agent run

# From your laptop — reach the mini's Ollama
idr connect m4mini.user-40example-2Ecom.idr 11434 --local-port 11434</code></pre>
      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Advanced:</strong> You may register multiple Device-IDs under the <em>same</em> host (e.g. two
        <code>m4mini</code> boxes for HA). <code>POST /resolve</code> then round-robins among online devices, like
        multiple A records. Most users prefer distinct host names as in the table above.
      </div>

      <h2>Canonical idrto URI</h2>
      <pre><code>idrto:&lt;host&gt;~&lt;entity-id&gt;/&lt;service-or-port&gt;[/&lt;path…&gt;][?query]</code></pre>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Segment</th><th>Rule</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>host</code></td><td>Dot-separated labels; device name is rightmost</td><td><code>laptop</code>, <code>db1.finance</code>, <code>edge.us-east</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>entity-id</code></td><td>Email, domain, or UUID; idr-escaped in authority</td><td><code>user-40example.com</code> → <code>user@example.com</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>service-or-port</td><td>Digit-first → port (optional <code>UDP</code> suffix); letter-first → named service</td><td><code>443</code>, <code>53UDP</code>, <code>ssh</code>, <code>ollama</code></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3>Examples</h3>
      <pre><code>idrto:laptop~user-40example.com/ssh
idrto:laptop~example.com/443
idrto:laptop.us-east~user-40example.com/53UDP
idrto:api~corp.com/443/v1/health?verbose=1</code></pre>

      <h2>idr-escape (entity segment)</h2>
      <p>Reserved characters in the <code>idrto:</code> authority use <code>-XX</code> uppercase hex:</p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Char</th><th>Encoded</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>@</code></td><td><code>-40</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>.</code></td><td><code>-2E</code> (in DNS label mode for <code>*.idr</code>)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>~</code></td><td><code>-7E</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>/</code></td><td><code>-2F</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>-</code></td><td><code>-2D</code></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Mirror HTTPS (metadata API)</h2>
      <pre><code>https://idr.to/&lt;host&gt;~&lt;url-encoded-entity-id&gt;/&lt;service-or-port&gt;[/path][?query]</code></pre>
      <p>
        Same logical target as <code>idrto:</code>, with percent-encoding instead of idr-escape for the entity.
        Used for browser <code>fetch</code>, OpenAPI metadata routes, and tooling that prefers HTTPS URLs.
        Hits the <strong>hosted idr.to API</strong> — returns JSON for connection setup, not proxied application bytes.
      </p>
      <pre><code>https://idr.to/laptop~user%40example.com/ollama
https://idr.to/laptop~user%40example.com/443/api/v1?source_host=workstation</code></pre>
      <div class="callout">
        Mirror URLs are <strong>not</strong> DEF hostnames. They use path-based routing on the apex <code>idr.to</code> host.
      </div>

      <h2>DEF encoding (<code>*.idr.to</code> relay)</h2>
      <p>
        For public HTTPS ingress via the optional <a href="https://github.com/idrto/https-relay">https-relay</a>,
        only the <strong>Host-Identity</strong> (<code>host~entity-id</code>) is encoded into the DNS label. Service and path live in the URL path.
      </p>
      <pre><code>Host-Identity:     laptop.us-east~user@example.com
DEF label:         dlaptop-2eus-2deast-7euser-40example-2ecom
FQDN (DEF FQHN):   dlaptop-2eus-2deast-7euser-40example-2ecom.idr.to
HTTPS URL:         https://dlaptop-2eus-2deast-7euser-40example-2ecom.idr.to/443/api/v1</code></pre>
      <p>
        DEF is generic byte-escape: lowercase letters and digits pass through; other bytes become <code>-hh</code> (e.g. <code>~</code> → <code>-7e</code>, <code>@</code> → <code>-40</code>).
        Labels longer than 62 DEF body characters use hash encoding (<code>h…</code>) — opaque and not client-decodable.
      </p>

      <h2>Synthetic <code>*.idr</code> hostnames</h2>
      <pre><code>&lt;host&gt;.&lt;idr-escaped-entity&gt;.idr</code></pre>
      <p>
        Tool-native hostnames for SSH, Postgres, and curl. Service is inferred from port (22 → ssh, 5432 → postgres, 11434 → ollama).
        Decoded locally by the idr client — no DNS registration required.
      </p>
      <pre><code>ssh user@laptop.user-40example-2Ecom.idr
psql postgresql://u@db1.finance.user-40example-2Ecom.idr:5432/mydb</code></pre>

      <h2>Personal vs Enterprise host depth</h2>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Tier</th><th>Host example</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Personal</td><td><code>laptop~user@example.com</code></td><td>Single-level host label only</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Enterprise</td><td><code>db1.us-east.finance~corp.com</code></td><td>Multi-level subdomain context within entity namespace</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Named services → ports</h2>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Service</th><th>Port</th><th>Transport</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>ssh</code></td><td>22</td><td>TCP</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>http</code></td><td>80</td><td>TCP</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>https</code></td><td>443</td><td>TCP</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>postgres</code></td><td>5432</td><td>TCP</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>ollama</code></td><td>11434</td><td>TCP</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>53UDP</code></td><td>53</td><td>UDP (unordered WebRTC datagram channel)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2 id="tunnel-wire">Tunnel wire (idr-tunnel-v1)</h2>
      <p>
        After ICE, peers multiplex streams over WebRTC. OPEN control frames on stream 0 use:
      </p>
      <pre><code>[0x01][stream_id u32 BE][host_len u16 BE][host utf8][port u16 BE][transport u8]</code></pre>
      <p><code>transport</code>: <code>0</code> = TCP, <code>1</code> = UDP. Full wire format:
        <a href="https://github.com/idrto/client/blob/main/docs/TUNNEL.md">client TUNNEL.md</a>.</p>

      <p>
        Related: <a href="/signaling">Signaling protocol</a> ·
        <a href="/architecture">Architecture</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  h1 { font-size: 2.25rem; margin: 0 0 1rem; }
  h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem; }
  h3 { font-size: 1.125rem; margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem; }
</style>
